In a locally convex space, the absolutely convex hull of a totally bounded set is totally bounded. The proof given here follows Proposition 3 of Bourbaki TVS II.25.

The better way to state this would be to assume `[UniformSpace E] [UniformAddGroup E]`. It feels a bit weird from the math point of view since the uniformity comes from the topology, but in many case it won't be defeq to `TopologicalAddGroup.toUniformSpace` (e.g your current lemma does not apply to normed spaces !). And it avoids a bunch of troubles in the proof.

Another thing : I think I would rather first state the result about the convex hull, and then use `convexHull_union_neg_eq_absConvexHull` to deduce the current result. I know Bourbaki does it the other way around (after all, what you wrote is stronger), but since we will have to *state* the convex hull statement anyway (which they don't !) I think we might as well split up the proof.
But of course this is a matter of taste

> The better way to state this would be to assume `[UniformSpace E] [UniformAddGroup E]`

@ADedecker Do I also need a hypothesis `(h : U = TopologicalAddGroup.toUniformSpace E)` to connect the uniformity to the locally convex topology?
Ah, I can use `UniformAddGroup.toUniformSpace_eq`
Sorry for the delay. Yes, you can use that, but it sounds a bit weird that you have to use it, let me have a look.
Well indeed you don't use it in the current version!

@ADedecker yes - originally I added `[UniformSpace E]` and `[UniformAddGroup E]` without removing `[TopologicalSpace E]` and `[TopologicalAddGroup E]`. Removing `[TopologicalSpace E]` and `[TopologicalAddGroup E]` resolved the issue.

> I think I would rather first state the result about the convex hull, and then use `convexHull_union_neg_eq_absConvexHull` to deduce the current result.

I have done this now.

Have you tried using [totallyBounded_iff_subset_finite_iUnion_nhds_zero](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Algebra/UniformGroup.html#totallyBounded_iff_subset_finite_iUnion_nhds_zero) ? I think it will make your life way easier.
What would the equivalent of `comp_mem_uniformity_sets` be for a Uniform Group?
`exists_closed_nhds_zero_neg_eq_add_subset` I guess?
@ADedecker thanks - this suggestion was a big improvement.

> `exists_closed_nhds_zero_neg_eq_add_subset` I guess?

I would have suggested [exists_nhds_zero_half](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Algebra/Monoid.html#exists_nhds_zero_half), but that works as well.
I think you'd make your life easier by just using `V + V` directly. Of course both are equal, but introducing smul here can only cause harm I think.
Thanks - that's much better - in fact gives us a more general result for `V+W`.

```suggestion
  use t', htf'
  simp only [iUnion_vadd_set, vadd_eq_add] at hts hts' ⊢
  calc convexHull ℝ s
    _ ⊆ convexHull ℝ (t + V) := convexHull_mono hts
    _ ⊆ convexHull ℝ t + convexHull ℝ V := convexHull_add_subset
    _ = convexHull ℝ t + V := by rw [hV₂.convexHull_eq]
    _ ⊆ t' + V + V := add_subset_add_right hts'
    _ = t' + (V + V) := by rw [add_assoc]
    _ ⊆ t' + (W + W) := add_subset_add_left (add_subset_add hV₃ hV₃)
    _ ⊆ t' + U := add_subset_add_left (add_subset_iff.mpr hW₂)
```
